name: Pleocoma behrensi LeConte, 1874
occurrenceRemarks: Seen flying. Overcast day after a rainstorm had passed. It was in a very thick coyote brush area in what I would call the Kennedy Creek Valley. It was flying. It was big. Like 1.5 " wide and 1" long with wings out. It caught my attention as something I had never seen before. It landed in the grassy duff under the coyote brush and was burrowing. With my finger I tried to uncover it so as to take a clear photo. But it was fast at re-burrowing so as soon as saw it in the open it began to burrow again. The ground duff was moist and soft. After a minute I left it be. iNaturalist was able to suggest a genus. I read that Pleocoma behrensi is the species found in the Bay Area so I selected that species. I might have to edit my selection as I learn more.

name: Pleocoma conjungens Horn, 1888
occurrenceRemarks: I saved this sucker from my cat, who had found it by a window. The night we found it it was raining (~1.5 inch/ day, and the second measurable rainfall of the season). The beetle was pretty active, trying to both crawl and fly. I returned it to the outdoors. It was cool to see a scaraboid beetle here in Santa Cruz County. I’ve never seen one before. I’m guessing at the species here.

name: Pleocoma sonomae Linsley, 1935
occurrenceRemarks: Date: 3 October 2018, 9:26 AM Location: Channel Trail, Trione-Annadel State Park, elevation approximately 160' Habitat: Mixed evergreen forest about 60m from creek. Immediate surrounding vegetation included bay laurel, poison oak, sword fern. This was about a minute's walking distance from the spot where I found my last rain beetle. Precipitation: This was following the second consecutive night of heavy rain, the first of the season. The weather had cleared briefly, but the rain picked up again for a short time during my hike, and it was during this rain that I found the beetle. The first two photos show the specimen in situ. I found this female sticking headfirst out of a burrow in the middle of the trail. She was not moving as I approached, but was responsive to being touched and was very active when I picked her up. After I set her down, she wandered to the leaf litter at the edge of the trail and began burrowing.
identificationRemarks: Appearance and locality . 4 lams . Cheers ! Gene St. Denis Sierra Nevada Research

name: Pleocoma rubiginosa rubiginosa
occurrenceRemarks: Pleocoma rubiginosa rubiginosa Hovore 1972 Chimney Peak Recreation Area , Kennedy Meadows Road , Kern Pleateu , Sierra Nevada Mountains, Tulare County, California, USA March 9, 2017 The first two pictures are of the Female , the third picture is of the Mating male, the forth Picture is of the Mating pair , and the Last Picture is of the Boys from the Kern Plateau ! And now the Description ...I just got back from spending 5 days ( 3/4/2017 to 3/9/2017 ) in the Kennedy Meadows Area in search of Pleocoma rubiginosa rubiginosa and I was not disappointed ! My good friend Garin Woo and his sister joined me the first day and we collected a handful each at sunset using Black lite traps and nets. The next day they had left and a major Blizzard hit me , dropping over a foot of fresh snow. I was off the pavement on a dirt road so, I stayed put and waited 2 days for the snow to melt and the Pleocoma to fly . 6 degrees the second night in the Blizzard and a balmy 22 degrees the third night with clearing skies .Finally the temps soared upward into the 70's and the Beetles started to Fly in Numbers ! So the 4th and 5th night I was able to collect an excellent / large series of beautiful freshly hatched male Pleocoma ! And as a Bonus Prize I found a Female Pleocoma rubiginosa rubiginosa on the last Night ! Setting her right in the lip of my net I was able to collect 6 Males who flew right in it ! Then the flights stopped as quickly as they began , with the main flight being 15 minutes in duration and then that was it . On the way home to Lake Tahoe my rig died and I had to have three different tow trucks work to get me and my Ford Expedition home ! That took Two extra days as the one Tow truck also had Mechanical problems half way home . It was still a great trip and the motor issue was fixed by my main mechanic in a half day, putting me back on the road ! Thank God for my Premium AAA Card and excellent Tow Truck operators ! These folks literally keep America Rolling ! The Male's length sizes ranged from 20mm to 30 mm and the Female was 22mm in length ( using stainless steel calipers ) . These are the last Pleocoma to fly until next Fall ! I am including the male and female pictures and they ( both sexes )are both the same length. Cheers and good Hunting to All ! Cheers ! Gene St. Denis Sierra Nevada Research

name: Pleocoma conjungens Horn, 1888
eventRemarks: One day after our first light rain of the season I put my black light/MV trap out, hoping I might find a rain beetle. Sure enough, there was one rain beetle in the trap the next morning, along with many moths. I assume it is the same species as . I thought that was pretty cool, until I found this guy and his friends. lifeStage:adult Sex: Size:26.3mm

name: Pleocoma conjungens Horn, 1888
eventRemarks: I found this guy in my black light/MV trap on 11 Nov. On 14 Nov, we were scheduled to pour the concrete foundation for our new barn, so I was up earlier (05:45) than usual to get ready. I let the dogs out for their morning business. The big dog stopped halfway through the doggy door to smell something on the doormat. When he got on through, I opened the door to find another rain beetle on the door mat. I turned on the flood light at the east side of the house, and followed the dogs on around to the side of the house, only to find 14 more rain beetles attracted to the flood light. 1/2" of rain on 11 Nov 2017, first significant rain of the season, less than 1/10" rain morning of 14 Nov 2017. lifeStage:adult Sex: Size:25.2mm length

After putting out the home made Blacklite traps at 5:00 am to 6:45 am on the morning of Jan. 14 , 2016 and the morning of Jan. 15 , 2016 we waited and had some Hot coffee. The show stopped cold at 6:45 am both mornings and then we did the long drive back to the Tahoe area. Tired but Happy . Gene St.Denis lifeStage:adult Sex:male Size:25 mm

name: Pleocoma badia hirsuta Davis, 1934
occurrenceRemarks: Joe and I went way down to south California , namely the Sanberg and Mt. Pinos area looking for Pleocoma and we were not disappointed. The My Home made Black light vein traps brought in Many male Pleocoma Linsleyi and some Beautiful male Pleocoma badia as well . 5:00 am to 6:45 am were the flight times and it was 52 degrees cloudy and rain scattered. Ground was soaked from a deluge 3 days before , then dry then scattered rain upon our arrival . We went back home to the Tahoe/ Reno area very happy. 6 laminae antennae fan segments, some may have 7 laminae . Cheers ! Gene St.Denis

name: Pleocoma hoppingi Fall, 1906
occurrenceRemarks: I drove down from Tahoe very carefully on 88 and then 49 thru the storms to Hwy 108 out of Sonora in the western Sierra's looking for some Pleocoma hoppingi males ( another " Snow Beetle " ) with 6 laminae . Turning east I headed up 108 Past Twain Hart to around 4,900 feet on turn outs and put out my home made Black light vein traps and waited . 6:00am to 6:45 am were the ticket for flight times. I kept a very nice series of active males and dumped out a couple hundred or more to repopulate the species. A giant puddle collected almost twenty for me ! 48 degrees , foggy, and raining . Snow and wet dirt were 50/50 . GST

name: Pleocoma rubiginosa Hovore, 1972
occurrenceRemarks: Headed south on Hwy 395 in calm , warmer, partial cloudy weather in search of the "Eastern Sierra Snow Beetle " AKA .. Pleocoma rubiginosa transierra .Collected 2 males at black lite and net ! Warmer weather caused snow melt at sundown . Pleocoma rubiginosa transierra.....5 Laminae... Awesome ! This Species has been a very elusive for me and everyone else ! The have widely spread out sites from Lee Vining down to Lone Pine and we have yet to have anyone identify a large colony site yet . The transierra SOP is for a handful to fly at a time large area , and this could last for several weeks or a couple months . They are very strong and fast flyers for their small size . They are smaller than rubiginosa rubiginosa and somewhat darker .Host plants are Pinus monophylla, the single-leaf pinyon, (alternatively spelled piñon) is a Pine, Jeffery Pine, and Old Large Oak trees. This area is West of Bishop, 6000' Bishop Creek area, Eastern Sierra Nevada, Inyo County, California, USA February 11, 2016 Cheers ! Gene St. denis

name: Pleocoma rubiginosa rubiginosa
occurrenceRemarks: 10 miles South of Kennedy Meadows , Southern Sierra Nevada, Tulare County, California, USA February 13, 2016 Size: 26 mm I headed down to Kennedy Meadows for a couple days in search of Pleocoma rubiginosa rubiginosa . This has not been an easy one to get .However, with the warmer weather and the snows melting I had a Dream ! Setting up my Black lite Vein traps and having net ready.. I waited at sun down with Very High Hopes and Prayers ! And I was not disappointed ( Thank the Lord ) ! Finally I was rewarded with a very nice series of males with net and Black lites ! Pleocoma rubiginosa...5 Laminae .. Right On ! Pleocoma rubiginosa rubiginosa has its World involving Habitat , Ecosystem, and Environment with Violent changes from Major fires Here on the Kern Plateau . These fire areas are now devoid of " Any " Pleocoma . Host Southern Sierra Plateau Habitat Zone- Pinyon Pine ,Digger Pine , Juniper, Common Sagebrush,Mountain Mahogany, and Rabbit Brush . Pinyon Pine is the Main Host Plant here for them . These are the last to fly for Pleocoma and can Have " Perculation Emergance " from January to April Depending on snow depth and snow melting amounts . Cheers ! Gene St. Denis

verbatimLocality: Logging Road South of Deadhorse Summit 6 miles , Hwy 89
name: Pleocoma shastensis Van Dyke, 1933
eventRemarks: I headed up north to Dead Horse summit on Highway 89 in a radical wind and rain storm October 14th and 15th 2016 . In the howling darkness south of Susanville on Highway 395 , 5 semi-tractor trailer rigs were blown over and the 5th one was right in front of me. The wind not only tipped the big rig over it lifted the Whole rig Over the highway fence and put it 40 feet from the road. Amazingly the driver was OK after crawling out and he had me call 911 for him. At times I would stop several times and wait for the gusts to pass , making the speed limit was not possible . I then continued way north past Susanville to 8 miles south of Dead horse summit and set out my home made black lite traps the next two nights and waited in the Pouring rain and howling winds. I was not disappointed ! The traps received a very nice series of males , every trap had 3 to 5 males in it. During the days I walked the Forrest service dirt roads in the immediate areas and located many more dead and dying , males from the flood conditions, as well as some still flying until Noon. It appears that the males will fly until out of energy once activated that DAY. They were not flying for several days at day break for 15 to 30 minutes at a time , as other Pleocoma do. This would explain why they are hard to find ! Many males had been driven over by other trucks on the roads in the immediate area and I have a couple handfuls to glue and repair this winter.Male sizes were from 23 mm to 34 mm . 48 degrees to 65 during the day and Heavy rain with soaked Muddy Earth. Stopped by Brady at Chico on the way home and gave him a couple handfuls of repair jobs and live ones. Cheers ! Gene St. Denis Sierra Nevada Research lifeStage: Sex:male Size:30 mm

name: Pleocoma rickseckeri Horn, 1888
occurrenceRemarks: Date/ Time: November 19 at approximately 11am Location: Annadel State Park, elevation approximately 160' Habitat: mixed evergreen/ riparian forest 50m from creek. Specifically, specimen was found in a stand of Douglas-fir trees. Precipitation: It was raining heavily at the time of collection. The city of Santa Rosa received 0.68 inches of rain on that day. This storm was the first really big rain of the season, as far as I can recall, but there had been several smaller storms earlier. Collection details: This male beetle was found planted head-first in the wet loam on the margin of a puddle on the hiking trail. Ground was covered in Douglas-fir needles. Beetle was motionless, with wings untucked from elytra, and did not react to being picked up. He became more alert and very active after drying off and being held for several minutes. Exhibited "burrowing" behavior--using his head to attempt to plow through the material of my glove. He remained energetic for the following 24 hours before he was frozen in preparation for pinning.
identificationRemarks: Very Nice find ! Keep up the good work ! Geno
informationWithheld: Coordinates hidden at the request of the observer

verbatimLocality: Wrightwood , Burn Area Dirt Road Turnouts
name: Pleocoma octopagina Robertson, 1970
eventRemarks: 12/22plus23plus24,2016 ,I drove down from lake Tahoe to the Wrightwood Burn area roads and back thru rain and snow storms . Meeting up with Mr.Garin Woo for the first morning , we set out our Home made Black lights and Mercury Vapor lite in high hopes of getting some hard to get Pleocoma octopagina Robertson 1970 male Rain Beetles . And we were not disappointed !! The rain flights started at 5 am and were intermittent until 6 am and then became steady until 7am and ended. Some were seen still flying around in the growing morning sun lite. We received a very nice series of Flying Large Newly Hatched Male Pleocoma octopagina . Precise Lengths of males were 22 mm to 36 mm with metal calipers . They come out in limited numbers and were quite Large and robust this year . I stayed out a couple more mornings solo . This was even in a completely and totally Burned out ( this August 2016 ) area .." Truly Toasted ". There is strong evidence to me that the majority of this area's Bush's ( highly resistant somewhat to fire ) are still alive under ground and can provide food for the Pleocoma grubs . I have have photo evidence that in adjacent past fires we have clear regrowth coming out of Completely burned terrain / Bushs . The laminae are extremely Thick and robust with their prominent " 8 fan segments " . They are very large and strong flyers for Pleocoma males and they came in to Garin's Mercury Vapor lite the strongest . I spent some time looking for females to no avail .On the way home in the Snow Storm I had to have it in four wheel drive from Bishop all the way home to Tahoe at 20 to 45 MPH ! Cheers ! Gene St. Denis Sierra Nevada Research lifeStage: Sex:male Size:34 mm

name: Pleocoma fimbriata LeConte, 1856
occurrenceRemarks: Pleocoma fimbriata -male - Pleocoma fimbriata - Male Pioneer and Hwy 88 3000 ', Amador County, California, USA October 17, 2015 Size: 33 mm During heavy rain in predawn to just after sunrise, located this fellow under street lite . Also then collected nice series under the lights. Many were found later during the day dead or just barley moving on the ground . Many ,many very flat road kills...sniff, sniff. Got some on my home made plexiglass black lite vein traps as well . 4 Laminae on antennae fan . 22 mm for the smallest runt to 35 mm for the largest furry with calipers. Soil was wet down past 12 inchs. No females or burrows located. Ravens , Racoon s, dogs, coyotes, and domestic cats were observed to consumed several . This species is one of the first to fly in High Sierra Nevada Fall Rain Storms . They are a Very large Pleocoma with shiny , Robust , and varied or raged morphology at times . Subdued golden setae with some darker setae . Thick in the area here north to Placerville . Cheers ! Gene St. Denis

name: Pleocoma blaisdelli Linsley, 1938
eventRemarks: I headed down to 49 and Don Pedro Reservoir 11/3/2015 ( during our first heavy soaker rains ) and set out a couple of my home made Plexiglas vein Black lite bucket traps just of a dirt road and waited . 56 degrees Rain. Finally the lord sent down more rain and at 5:00 am to 6:10 am a very nice series of males newly hatched , very sharp horned , and scratch free ! Very Shiny black elytra covers and golden brown Fur ! The males lengths were exactly ( on metal calipers ) 20 mm to 28 mm long. gst ?Gene St. Denis, lifeStage: Sex:male Size:25 mm

name: Pleocoma hovorei La Rue, 2007
occurrenceRemarks: I stopped at the Paynes creek area off of Hwy 36 in high hopes . I located a series of Pleocoma Hovorei males under lites in lite rain @ 48 degrees and 6:00am . 7 Laminae . These are not the first to fly like shastensis . They are slow to fly and it takes alot of precipitation to soak the highly absorbent volcanic soil . Then they will Fly in what we call slow " perculation emergence " over a couple months sometimes . Cheers ! Gene St. Denis

name: Pleocoma fimbriata LeConte, 1856
occurrenceRemarks: Male and female. After first good rain in the fall. Determination made by Frank Havore when found. We managed to dig out both male and female at the same site. A special memory of a special time with Frank.
identificationRemarks: Pleocoma fimbriata male and female ( larger ) . This area has a different species than the normal fimbriata . The obvious difference is the Red pronotum . More specimens are needed to pin it down . However , I believe that the isolated Sutter butte colony has enough deference's to be on its own as a sub or even a new species . Pbsands , I could use any specimens you find to be able to describe them more . Close up pictures ... club segment pictures etc. would be good as well . Cheers ! Gene St . Denis Sierra Nevada Research

name: Pleocoma behrensi LeConte, 1874
occurrenceRemarks: Male. Tilden Regional Park, near Jewel Lake. Second photo shows a size comparison between a US quarter and a male's emergence burrow.

name: Pleocoma behrensi LeConte, 1874
occurrenceRemarks: Tilden Regional Park, near Jewel Lake. First photo shows a female at her burrow opening; second photo shows the "bottom" portion of an excavated burrow (different from the one in the first photo). The dirt was pretty firm and I was able to dig out a good-sized chunk containing the burrow. After carefully scraping away about half of the dirt, I managed to reveal a longitudinal section of the bottom portion of the burrow. I placed the female at the bottom of the burrow where I had found her and took the picture.

verbatimLocality: Gas Station , Intersection of Hwy 74 + Hwy 243
name: Pleocoma australis Fall, 1911
eventRemarks: Netted 2 under the Local Gas station Lights , the rest were squashed flat and useless . They are dark and once you shine some lite on them they show off some nice colors! Cheers ! Gene St. Denis Sierra Nevada Research lifeStage: Sex:male Size:31 mm

name: Pleocoma australis Fall, 1911
occurrenceRemarks: Pleocoma australis - Gas Station , Intersection of Hwy 74 + Hwy 243 , Riverside County, California, USA November 16, 1973 Size: 31 mm Netted 2 under the Local Gas station Lights , the rest were squashed flat and useless .Foggy and flying 5:45 to 6:20 am . They are dark ( dark form without added Lighting pic number 4) and once you shine some lite on them they show off some nice colors! (Pics Number 1,2,+3 ) It should be noted that Pleocoma punticollis and Pleoocoma australis are prone to blending or cross breeding in some areas . This occurs in many Beetles and insects . The trick is to find pure breeding species colony's for a baseline collection data base . Cheers ! Gene St. Denis Sierra Nevada Research
